{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"This is a brute force method using calculus. Assume we have a right triangle "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ABC"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":" with coordinates "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"A(0,0)"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":", "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"B(0,3)"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":", and "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"C(3,0)"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":". This way, the centroid is at point "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"1,1"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":". Now, assume our line has y intercept "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\alpha"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":" and crosses through the centroid to make a triangle with the x and y axis. The equation for the line would then be "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"y=(1-\alpha)x+\alpha"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":". To find the x intercept, we set "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"y=0"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":" to get "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"x=\frac{\alpha}{\alpha -1}"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":". Then the formula for the triangle, which we'll generalize to a rectangle, would be "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"A=\alpha\cdot\frac{\alpha}{\alpha -1}"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":". Then the ratio of the yellow triangle to the quadrilateral would then be "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\frac{A}{3\cdot3 - A}"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":". We can now take the derivative and solve for "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\alpha"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":", giving us our answer. "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\begin{aligned}&\frac{d}{d\alpha}\frac{\frac{\alpha^2}{\alpha -1}}{9-\frac{\alpha^2}{\alpha -1}}= \frac{d}{d\alpha}\frac{\frac{\alpha^2}{\alpha -1}}{\frac{9\alpha-9-\alpha^2}{\alpha -1}}=\frac{d}{d\alpha}\frac{\alpha^2}{9\alpha-9-\alpha^2}\\ &\frac{18\alpha^2-18\alpha-2\alpha^3-9\alpha^2+2\alpha^3}{(9\alpha-9-\alpha^2)^2} = \frac{9\alpha^2-18\alpha}{(9\alpha-9-\alpha^2)^2}=0 \\ &9\alpha^2-18\alpha=0 \implies \alpha=2 \end{aligned}"}],"attrs":{"inline":false}},{"type":"text","text":" Putting this back in the ratio function, we get "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":" \frac{2^2}{9(2)-9-2^2}=\boxed{\frac{4}{5}}"}],"attrs":{"inline":false}}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Simply do 1 times 2 times 3 times 4 times 5 and you get 120."}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"This problem is similar to a "},{"type":"text","text":"balance puzzle","marks":[{"attrs":{"href":"","target":"_blank"},"type":"link"}]},{"type":"text","text":", except this time each islander is like a coin and the seesaw is like the balance.  Since the target islander weighs differently than the others, the least number of weighings for "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"c = 12"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":" islanders will be "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\lceil \log_3 (2c + 1) \rceil = \boxed{3}"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}

